    "<p>Medievalist; first woman to curator of a major British museum; Keeper the Department of Architecture and Sculpture, Victoria and Albert Museum, London, 1938-1942.": [],
    "Longhurst's early life is uncertain due to her extreme private nature.": [],
    "She was likely the daughter of Henry Longhurst (1824-1895), a successful thought modest draper, and Caroline Louisa Taylor (Longhurst).": [],
    "She was educated privately (according to herself) but never, apparently, formally.": [],
    "Longhurst used her inheritance left to her by her father to travel in Europe, privately experiencing and studying art, particularly medieval sculpture.": [],
    "She published articles as a private scholar in the <em>Burlington Magazine</em>.": [],
    "Longhurst volunteered at the Victoria & Albert Museum after the First World War, then moving to a temporary cataloger position in 1924, the year <a href=\"/maclagane\">Eric Maclagan</a> ascended to the directorship.": [],
    "She was made a museum assistant in 1926, because of her knowledge of early sculpture.": [],
    "The same year she published <em>English Ivories</em> and <em>Catalogue of Carvings in Ivory</em>.": [],
    "part 1, 1927, and part 2, 1929 of the Victoria and Albert Museum.": [
